PHASE 5: RENDERING PERFORMANCE OPTIMIZATIONS
=============================================

The existing rendering pipeline has no spatial awareness: every expanded
node is drawn regardless of whether it is visible on screen or large enough
to see. On large trees like /usr with many directories expanded, this means
tens of thousands of nodes are submitted to OpenGL every frame, making
interaction sluggish.

Per-directory display lists remain cached (geometry built once, replayed
via glCallList). The tree-level display list cache (which bakes all
per-directory calls into a single list) is replaced by a per-frame culled
tree walk, since the culled walk skips most directories and is faster than
replaying a massive uncached list.

Step 5.1 - Frustum and screen-space size culling
  [x] Extract view frustum planes from the projection-modelview matrix
      at the start of each frame
  [x] Compute world-space bounding volumes per directory subtree for
      each visualization mode (DiscV, MapV, TreeV)
  [x] In each mode's recursive draw function, test the directory's
      bounding volume against the frustum; skip the entire subtree if
      fully outside
  [x] Skip subtrees whose projected screen size falls below a threshold
      (e.g., 2 pixels) -- natural LOD without geometry simplification
  [x] Replace tree-level display list (3-stage system) with per-frame
      culled tree walk that calls per-directory display lists directly
  [X] Verify: all three modes render correctly, camera interaction is
      smooth on large expanded trees

  Checkpoint: User tests with ./builddir/fsv /usr, fully expands several
  directories, orbits camera, and confirms rendering is significantly
  faster and visually correct.

Step 5.2 - Label distance culling
  [x] During label drawing passes, estimate the projected screen height
      of each label from camera distance and world-space size
  [x] Skip labels whose projected height is below a legibility threshold
      (e.g., 6 pixels)
  [x] Verify: labels appear/disappear smoothly as the camera zooms in/out;
      no visual artifacts

  Checkpoint: User tests by zooming in and out on a large expanded tree
  and confirms labels appear when readable, disappear when too small,
  and rendering is faster when zoomed out.

Step 5.3 - Reduce tree walks during collapse/expand animation
  [x] During colexp animation, only rebuild per-directory display lists
      for the directory whose geometry actually changed (geom_expanded
      transition), not every frame
  [x] On animation frames where no per-directory lists are stale, skip
      the Stage 0 "rebuild stale" pass and go directly to the culled
      tree walk
  [x] Verify: expand/collapse animations are visually correct and
      noticeably smoother on large trees

  Checkpoint: User tests by expanding and collapsing directories on a
  large tree and confirms animations are smooth and visually correct.

Step 5.4 - Optimize wireframe outline pass
  [x] In TreeV and MapV high-detail rendering, the entire geometry is
      redrawn in wireframe mode for black edge outlines (a full extra
      tree walk). Replace with a more efficient technique:
      - Use glPolygonOffset to render filled geometry slightly offset,
        then render outlines only for nearby/visible nodes, OR
      - Apply outline culling: skip wireframe pass for subtrees below
        a projected size threshold
  [x] Verify: edge outlines still appear on nearby nodes; visual quality
      is acceptable; frame rate improves on large trees

  Checkpoint: User tests in MapV and TreeV with many expanded directories
  and confirms outlines look acceptable and performance is improved.

Step 5.5 - Pick rendering optimization
  [x] Apply the same frustum/size culling to pick rendering
      (geometry_draw_for_pick) so that only visible, large-enough nodes
      are drawn into the pick FBO
  [x] Consider keeping pick FBO valid during camera pans where the scene
      has not changed (only the viewpoint), and re-rendering pick only
      when geometry or expansion state changes
      (Pick FBO already uses lazy invalidation — re-rendered only when
      ogl_color_pick() is called. Camera pans change the projection so
      the FBO must be re-rendered. Current approach is already optimal.)
  [x] Verify: node selection via click and hover still works correctly
      for all visible nodes; no misidentification

  Checkpoint: User tests by hovering and clicking on nodes in a large
  expanded tree and confirms correct node identification and improved
  responsiveness.


PHASE 6: KEYBOARD PANNING
=========================

Step 6.1 - Arrow key and WASD camera control
  [x] Make the GL area widget focusable and grab focus on click, so it
      receives key events
  [x] Add GDK_KEY_PRESS handling to viewport_cb(): arrow keys and WASD
      call camera_pan() with a fixed step size
      - DiscV: pans the 2D top-down view target
      - MapV/TreeV: pans the 3D camera target in screen-space directions
  [x] Verify: arrow keys and WASD pan in all three modes; keys
      do not interfere with text entry widgets (search bar, etc.)

Step 6.2 - Smooth frame-driven keyboard panning
  [x] Track key held state (booleans per direction) instead of relying
      on OS key repeat; filter out auto-repeat key press events
  [x] Add GDK_KEY_RELEASE_MASK and handle GDK_KEY_RELEASE to clear
      held state; clear all held keys on focus loss
  [x] Drive panning from a GLib idle callback that runs every frame
      while any pan key is held, giving instant response and smooth
      frame-rate-coupled movement
  [ ] Verify: panning starts instantly on key press with no delay,
      movement is smooth, and stops cleanly on key release

  Checkpoint: User tests keyboard panning in all three modes and
  confirms instant response, smooth continuous movement, and clean
  stop on key release. Search bar typing still works.


NOTES
=====
- Each step should leave the code compilable and runnable
- User tests after each phase completion
- The #if 0 block in gui.c (lines 1472-1605) contains unused code with
  additional deprecated APIs (GtkTooltips, gtk_check_menu_item_set_show_toggle).
  We can either port or delete it.
- geometry.c uses ~267 legacy GL calls (glBegin/glEnd, display lists, etc.)
  These work fine under GL compatibility profile and are NOT changed in this
  migration. A future project can move to modern GL core profile.
- The lib/getopt.c, lib/getopt1.c, lib/scandir.c, lib/fileblocks.c are
  POSIX polyfills and need no changes.
